deck_excerpt: First attempt at yugioh deck building, please do not be harsh.
deck_description: My first attempt to build a red supernova dragon deck. Still an amateur yugioh player learning its deckbuilding process.

people say that charmers aren't good, well, its just because they dont wanna take the time to make it good.  this deck has a 50% chance to otk if you can play it right, and i put a lil loving touch on this one so i think it'll be good.  i use this deck alot on yugioh dueling nexus, and i do pretty well. charmers have lots of ways to get each other out, but the main problem they have is the fact that the charmers themselves have no negates. i run the deck in a casual way, but ive took it to some tournaments and left a big arse mark. though it does need some touch ups.  I think the decks biggest enemy is something like altergiest, as they have lots of ways to get the other cards out, and then put alot of negates on the board. ive played around altergiest only once, but it was a best of three match so i lost.... but this deck still puts up a fight.  iguess you should really consider this deck  charmer fur hire melffys deck, cause it runs more fur hire cards then it does shaddolls. i run fur hire mainly because most of the monsters have the attributes that are used by the spirit charmers (earth, wind, water, and fire). they do have really cool effects though, all of thm can ss anther one during your main phase. it helps to get more peeps on the board to link away for anything really.  i didn't add the side deck in, but you should put cards like ash and nib to help u out when you face something that gives the deck a real problem (a.k.a altergiest)  anyway though, have fun with it!

That's my casual Bandit Keith Deck. 1 - I tried my best to remain loyal to the old school theme, and at the same time I added some new cards to give this deck a boost. 2 - I didn't add Desperado Barrel Dragon because I thought it would be weird to see it on the same deck with the old Barrel Dragon. However, you can replace one of the high level monster and run 1 copy of Desperado Barrel Dragon or run both them (the old and the new Barrel Dragon). 3 - I added 8 normal monsters and 8 effect monsters. Most of them are DARK machines because the Spider needs dark machine monster to activate it's effect. However, I thought it would be unfair to leave Robotic Knight, Bugroth and Guardian of the Throne out of this deck. They deserve a spot. Every single normal monster is an old school one. Bandit Keith didn't use a lot of effect monsters (if I'm not mistaken he used Barrel Dragon, Blast Sphere and Machine King, but that's it), so I added some. 4 - 3 high level monster are classic ones (Pendulum Machine, Barrel Dragon and Machine King) Keith used in the anime. The other 3 monster I thought they'd fit the theme of this deck, since they're dark machine monsters, and one of them has an effect that is about tossing a coin. You can use Launcher Spider and/Slot Machine and replace the Pendulum Machine and/or other non classic monster if you want to. 5 - Spell and Traps are cards keith used in the anime. I'm not running 3 copies of 7 completed because I think it'd be too much. As you can see I tried to remain loyal to our machine theme here. I hope you all enjoy this deck. It's not OP, but it has some power. I love these decks that use old and new cards together.

deck_excerpt: DECK MACHINA INFINITRACK PARA TORNEOS FUN
deck_description: UN DECK CONSISTENTE, SIN USAR MACHINA METAL CRUNCHER PARA SER MAS ECONOMICO, DE PREFERENCIA USAR METALCRUNCHER PERO PARA LOS QUE NO CUENTAN CON EL ESTA ES UNA ALTERNATIVA ECONOMICA.

Golden Castle Gren. One of the best rogue contenders this format due to it's ability to play a lot of board breaking cards, as well as being able to play the arguably the best hand trap against the current meta without being hindered by it at all, in fact it benefits massively from it (read on if you have guessed what the card is).  There are ultimately 2 win conditions that the deck has. The first is simply banish enough cards and summon Gren Maju to swing for massive damage and the game. With cards like Gizmek, Golden Castle, Pot Of Desires and Eater Of Millions being such amazing mass banishing cards this is a fairly acheivable goal.     The second win condition relies on being able to use the Rank 8 package as well as the board breaking cards to either force a win via Draglubion/Numeron Dragon, or put them in a position that they cannot claw back due to the immense resources they have exhausted. The main deck features 11 Level 8's (and 1 in the extra) to achieve this goal. The Danger package acts as a triple threat. They can act as big beatsticks, removal cards and pseudo draw cards. Hex Trude acts a beatstick and a removal card and Gizmek acts as a deck thinner, Gren Maju feeder and removal card all in 1. Combine the 11 main deck level 8's with Glife, Golden Castle and Pot of desires you effectively have half a deck of level 8's.  The hand traps are easy to explain. Ash is there as it's a generic hand trap that can hit anything I wish, and is particularly useful when preventing Eldlich from hitting field via Sanguine. Nibiru is there because combo decks such as Dragon Link and Tri-brigade have really cone back into being  with the banning of Calamaties. And finally Dimension Shifter..... If you're deck isn't particularly graveyard centric or benefits from banishing, you play this card. See how quick this stops the meta dead. Literally a game ender in it's own right.     The remainder of the cards are simple. Raigeki is there to push through Tri-Brigade and Dino's (most players summon Dolka over Laggia due to 2 monster negates being arguably more effective on the current format) without sacrificing the OTK if using Dark Ruler and cards with Forbidden Droplets. It's also fairly useful against Zoodiac Drident, AA Sky Zeus e.t.c. Harpie's Feather Duster to blowout control decks, Super Poly is just nuts thus format and reborn to bring back whatever you want.  The extra deck consists of super poly targets, N'tiss because Dogmatika is still a thing, Rank 8 package of Dingirsu for non targeting removal, recovering a banished Gizmek and field protection. Sanaphond stops graveyard centric decks from special summoning from the grave snd Dragubilon, Numeron Dragon and Hope Harbinger for the OTK. AA Zeus is there if you cannot quite OTK and need something to disrupt an opponents attempt to fight back. A simple Knightmare package and BLS round off the extra deck nicely.     Side deck. Phantazamay is there for Tri-Brigade/Dragon link, as i really do want to see my board breaker cards against these decks and Phantazamay by drawing extra cards and targeting protection too. Lightning Storm effectively acts as an extra 3 copies of Raigeki/Haripe's. The traps consist mainly of floodgates. TCBOO to really cripple predominantley monotype decks, Imperial Order to prevent Invoked/Shaddoll packages and also preventing floodgate removal via Twisters or Cyclone. Macros Cosmos banishes everything, so is highly effective against combo and control decks such as Eldlich alike. Dimension Ground is an additional nasty against combo as is not as vulnerable to S/T removal as TCBOO. Red Reboot to shutdown control decks for either an OTK or mass trap blowout.  Feel free to rate/comment.

deck_excerpt: This is mostly a 'for-fun' deck. SS are not a super competitive archetype, but are they fun? HELL YEAH!
deck_description: This version mostly tries to stick to just SS with a few tech cards, such as the Kaijus to work with battleball. I run 5 of them as there isn't really a coherent way to get them into your hand, except by drawing them. The deck does lack some drawpower, so if that's your idea, maybe try the SS pendulum who lets you draw by tributting itself, or a geargia engine (3x Geargiauger 1x Geargiaccelator) that helps turbo into Gear Gigant X more often for consistency and good search (i say maybe cut 3 magnet and 1 soulfiresuit). I was thinking of adding 1 geargiano to allow X to get off his final effect (trust me, he's never around for long), but maybe that's a bit too much deviation from the deck's playstyle. I do like my protection, so that's why i play 2 flutist and 3 soulfiresuit. You ALWAYS want a soulfiresuit in hand to protect yo shit! Gotta sit on that thicc booty. Most of the time, big benki is only summoned out from the grave via scarecrow, or flutist if you're in that situation so i run just the 1 of him. I do like the 1 fist as it gives you a constant tuner that can keep coming back, granted you've protected your synchros, but it's only a once per turn, hence the 1 copy. Also, 3 scarecrows are a must imo, as there are many times when I've almost gone through all 3 in a duel, he never stays around that long either. Him and soulpiercer are the bets wombo combo starter in the deck, so u gota get the most out of em.  Any tips or advice on how to improve the deck further is always appreciated. Gotta dash, hope you guys enjoyed.

deck_excerpt: What's this? The Artifacts are actually an archetype and not JUST an engine? Impossible!!
deck_description: So, this is another non-meta fave of mine. It's good if you want to play a deck with unique mechanic and give your opponent a chance to play the game, then you both can have some fun. Shock horror, I know.  But aside from that jest, the deck itself is fairly decent. It can brick sometimes and the archetype itself does need more support, but the way it works right now seems fairly solid. Moraltech and Sythe are fairly self explanatory. I play the 1 Beagalltach to act as the 4th Vajra, and the main way your gonna get some solid recursion from the grave is with Failnaught and BTTF, which also pairs well with Trap Trick. I then play the Achilleshield and Aegis to protect yo shit when u summon em during ur oppenents turn. They aren't that beefy so u gotta protec those dudes somehow. I originally was playing an extra Achille, but had to cut it and an MST for 2 BTTF for the more late game plays. Speaking of MST, they act as your extra 2 copies of ignition. The deck needs more ways to pop off and trigger itself (a field spell pls Konami) as otherwise...you're pretty fucked. Aside from that, Breakthrough skill is a poor mans infinite impedance and BTTF I've already mentioned. Track trick just helps with consistency and getting a 1st turn sanctum and then go off.  To help with the deck, I recommend an engine that uses a strong normal summon, as you don't really use that at all during your turn. For draw power, you could use a spellbook one, but I prefer to be able to go into the Artifact Link monster, Dagda first turn. It helps u get the artifacts u need during ur opponents turn and revive a fallen one when it dies (which it probably will with that weak ass attack). Ideally the scrap engine is much better giving access to synchros and more cool combos with accesscode talker, but as scrap raptor does not exist in the tcg and trickstars are kinda dead right now with their field spell at 1, the next best thing is Evil eye. It works quite similar to the previous 2 engines and does help mill itself out of the deck with Basilius sending it's own field spell, so once you've used it, you're not running the risk of drawing them later which is kinda neat. Wish the field spell was as good as the Trickstar one, being able to lock down pesky traps/spells is always nice. Try experimenting with different engines and see what happens tho,  Welp, there u have it. My pure Artifact deck. As always, any feedback or tips you guys have is always appreciated. But I gotta dash, hope you guys enjoyed.

deck_excerpt: Use the Sacred Beasts and there supports to give you a powerful start and leave the duel with your opponents quivering in fear!
deck_description:
This Deck type is a hybrid of the three previous decks and its goal is Summoning the three Sacred Beasts and their fusion, Armityle the Chaos Phantasm. While this Deck can use cards that allow the three Sacred Beasts to function, it is very taxing on Deck space and consistency. A better alternative is to focus on two or even only one of the three Sacred Beasts and use the first effect of Dark Summoning Beast to summon the remaining ones at a time. The ideal hand is as follows:
  • Opening of the Spirit Gates
  • Dark Beckoning Beast
  • Dark Summoning Beast
  • Chaos Summoning Beast
  • Awakening of the Sacred Beasts
First, activate Opening of the Spirit Gates to search for one of the Sacred Beasts (I suggest Raviel since it requires 3 fiend type monsters which is more restrictive than the other two).  Next, summon Dark Beckoning Beast to the field and activate its effect to search for one out of the two remaining sacred beasts (from this point I would suggest hamon since Uria needs continuous trap cards in the graveyard to determine its attack points). After that, use Dark Beckoning Beast other special ability to make an additional summon and tribute Beckoning for Dark Summoning Beast. Now, use Dark Summoning Beasts special ability to tribute itself and summon Raviel to the field. From the graveyard, activate Summoning Beasts ability to banish itself and add the last sacred beast. Since you have Raviel on the field, which is a lv 10 monster, activate Spirit Gates other affect to search your deck for a continuous spell card (suggest: add Temple of the Kings to your hand in order to activate Awakening of the Sacred Beast the same turn). Next activate Spirit Gates final effect to discard Chaos Summoning Beast to the graveyard in order to summon Dark Summoning Beast from the graveyard. Activate Summoning Beasts special ability from the graveyard to add Fallen Paradise to your hand and activate its effect right away to draw two new cards. Use Dark Summoning Beast effect again to summon Hamon. From then on, you should have the cards to summon Armityle the Chaos Phantasm and win the duel.

deck_excerpt: Combining Time Thief, Raidraptor, and Phantom Knights makes a strong combo deck, that can flex into the rank 4 toolbox, and has a strong grind game in
deck_description:
Time Thief contain some of the strongest cards in a vacuum, but has locked out of true meta relevance since it's release. Time Thief Regulator is a one card full combo, but is completely stopped by Ash Blossom, but can also be a great way to bait hand traps to let you use the other 1 card rank 4's, or the rest of your hand, that will almost always have a way to at least make a rank 4, opening combo lines for you.

  Although the deck appears to have a lot of garnets, as long as you have 2 Raidraptors in deck, the full combo is still possible. The Rokket package is also in theory the same as opening Regulator, but locks you out of the strongest end board the deck consistently has, but should be more then enough to shut down rough and low tier decks. This list can be trimmed back slightly to have more hand traps, or other potential starters or extenders.   The 1 card full combo is simply Time Thief Regulator. Summon Regulator, using its effect to summon Winder, and Adjuster, sending Bezel Ship and adding Retrograde from deck. Making Force Strix, adding the copy of Singing Lanius, and reviving a copy of Bezel Ship from grave by detaching the other material from Force Strix. Making Wise Strix and summoning a copy of Raider's Wings from deck, then using the Bezel Ship and Raider's Wings to make the second copy of Force Strix, detaching to add Strangle Lanius from deck to hand, and causing Wise Strix to set a copy of Rank-up Shave Force from the deck, then using that Rank-up to revive the first copy of Force Strix, then stacking Cyber Dragon Infinity from your extra deck. Using the second copy of Force Strix and the Wise Strix, make Rusty Bardiche, using Rusty's effect to send a copy of Ancient Cloak to grave to set a copy of Shade Brigandine from deck. By banishing Ancient Cloak, add a copy of Silent Boots from deck to hand, giving you hand of Strangle Lanius and Silent Boots. Summon the copy of Strangle Lanius from your hand, locking you into DARK monsters. Use Strangle Lanius effect to revive the Singing Lanuis from the grave, then summon Time Thief Redoer. Revive the Raider's Wings from the grave by detaching a materiel from Redoer, then flip the Shade Brigandine, summoning it as a level 4 monster. Using the Shade Brigandine and the Raider's Wings to summon Time Thief Perpetua, and activating it's effect to attach a copy of Time Thief Chronocorder to the Redoer. Activate Redoer, detaching Chronocorder specifically, then reviving Chronocorder by it's own effect. Special summon the Silent Boots from your hand, then link off the Boots and Chronocorder into I:P Masquerena. banish the Boots from your grave, adding a Fog Blade or Phantom Knights Claw from your deck, and set it along with the Time Thief Retrograde. End the turn, returning the Redoer. During the opponents standby phase, attach the top card of the opponent's deck, then attach a copy of Time Thief Flyback to Redoer as well. As well, activating Perpetua's revive effect by detaching Raider's Wings to summon the Winder, and activate its effect, adding a copy of any Time Thief card from deck to hand.   this combo ends on a +8, with a omni-negate from Infinity, a quick effect non-targeting spin to the top of the deck, as well as a spin from the Knightmare Unicorn that can be made with the I:P Masquerane, a spell/trap negate, that attaches the spell/trap negated to a Time Thief xyz, a monster negate, and a D.D. Crow like effect with the Flyback detached by Redoer.

deck_excerpt: Vendread Deck using small impcantation, phantom knights and Zombie World engine
deck_description:
This deck uses the spammability of Revendread Origins to go into Knightmare gryphon, rusty bardiche, beatrice and even king calamity on your opponents turn. I won't write any fixed combos here, as you have to be flexible, because every hand needs a different order. But still some important info for beginners:
  • Evolution is once per turn, origin is not (which is amazing)
  • Vendread Battlelord can search for chalislime
  • Use battlelord effect with monsters to prevent handtraps (especially nibiru)
  • Always banish evolution with battlelord, because it is useless in the graveyard
  • If you have already used candoll you can summon bookstone with chalislime to recycle origin
  • Always tribute impcantations ASAP, they lock you out of your extra deck
  • Solitaire is just another copy of uni-zombie
  • Use beatrice to send banshee on your turn and glow-up bloom on your opponents
Why I chose:
  • Impcantations: Vendreads can only work if they have their ritual spells, if they have 2+ they can play through multiple handtraps, if they have 0 they cant play at all
  • Zombie World Engine: balerdroch is such a pain to deal with and zombie world shuts down many meta decks atm, so a pretty obvious choice if you can go into beatrice
  • Phantom Knights engine: Rusty Bardiche is broken and easy to go into mid-combo,  also the phantom knight monsters and fog blades aren't dead in hand so yeah
I am waiting for august when volnigesh comes around because then this deck can consistently make Dawn King Kali Yuga on your opponents turn (!!!), so stay tuned

deck_excerpt: The fury of the jungle has taken shape! It's time to wrap our opponent in the vines of defeat! La furia de la jungla ha tomado forma! Es hora de envo
deck_description:
Deck creado por: Darklab Objetivo: Quemar la vida de tu oponente infinitamente con Amazoness Archer y Gigaplant Link a la demostración del Deck: >>>>> https://youtu.be/tFr6hErObNk <<<<< Para iniciar, debemos invocar a Cherubini, para lo cual tendremos muchísimos extenders. Luego de eso, dependiendo de cuántos tengamos, nos decantaremos por una de las 3 posibles rutas (explicadas en el video). Extenders para iniciar el combo:
  • Tour guide from the underworld: Vale x3. Trae al campo a Graff o al Edge imp (el otro lo envías al cementerio usando a Cherubini). En todo caso, es el mejor normal summon del deck.
  • Fiendish rhino warrior: Vale x2. Envía al cementerio el mismo target que la Tour guide, aunque no aprovecha el cuerpo extra. Necesita otro extender sí o sí.
  • Junk forward: Se invoca de modo especial desde la mano si no controlas monstruos, por lo que si lo robas, debe ser el primero en invocarse.
  • Kagemucha knight: Se invoca de modo especial cuando invocas otro monstruo de nivel 3 de modo normal. Ojo que puede perder timing.
  • Psychic wheeleder: Se invoca si ya tienes otro monstruo de nivel 3, aunque sólo es una vez por turno.
  • Psychic tracker: Igual que el anterior.
  • Gilasaurus: Se invoca casi gratuitamente. Ojo que el rival puede invocar algo del cementerio, aunque usualmente eso no es un problema.
  • Fossil dig: Trae al Gilasaurus.
  • Foolish burial: Puedes enviar a Cloak para robar a Boots o Brigandine, o en su defecto enviar uno de los targets de la Tour guide.
  • Emergency teleport: Trae a uno de los Psychic gratis.
  • Monster reborn: Extender por excelencia. Trae de vuelta algo que ya hayas usado.
Pros:
  • Deck extremadamente consistente, tiene pocos bricks y/o garnets.
  • Versátil. Se adapta a los recursos que tengamos en mano.
  • Protegido constantemente por Apollousa, por lo que es difícil de contrarrestarlo una vez toca el campo.
  • El Deck usa burn infinito, por lo que no importa cuántos LP tenga el oponente.
  • No requiere demasiados recursos para realizar el combo, con 2 es suficiente para iniciar.
  • Puede baitear hantraps tempranas con los extenders suficientes.
Contras:
  • Aunque el burn es infinito, cartas como Ghost Sister que aumentan constantemente los LP arruinarán la estrategia.
  • Aún teniendo protección, el Deck es susceptible a Nibiru, Impermanence y Called by the grave si son usados correctamente.
  • A pesar de ser consistente, si robamos 3 garnets, será gg.
  • Si destruyen a Cherubini antes de activar su efecto y no hay forma de invocarlo del cementerio, también es gg.

deck_excerpt: Isolde into Arma, folks. Does anything you want.
deck_description:
Ok so the first step is: Make Isolde. If you can make Isolde, you have FTK. How can we get there? Any 2 Igknights do the job. Open 4 Igknights? Add Gearfried to your board in 4 summons. Opening Renaud, Ogier, ROTA, Heritage, and/or Durendal alongside 2 Igknights and you get Gearfried protection alongside your combo. So what is the line after making Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights?
  1. Send 4 Equip Spells to the GY, including Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to summon Armageddon Knight. If your opening hand included Arma, Plaguespreader Zombie, or Cyber-Stein, you can summon Dark Grepher instead and adapt the combo (it isn't that hard, but if you need an explanation just ask in the comments).
  2. Send Plaguespreader off of Arma.
  3. Revive Plaguespreader, make Crystron Halqifibrax using Isolde and Plaguespreader to summon Vylon Cube from the deck.
  4. Cube + Arma to make Shooting Riser Dragon, sending any level 3 Igknight, and Cube's effect to search D.D.R. - Different Dimension Reincarnation.
  5. Add back Phoenix Blade, banishing Arma and any other warrior, then pitch it for D. D. R. to summon back Arma, sending Stein.
  6. Overlay Arma and Riser into Number 60: Dugares the Timeless, and revive Stein (be sure to put it under an EMZ).
  7. Make Cross-Sheep using Dugares and Halq. Activate Stein's effect to summon Lyrilusc - Independent Nightingale (be sure to summon it in one of Cross-Sheep's zones).
  8. Cross-Sheep will trigger, summoning back Cube. Use Nightingale's effect to burn for 500.
  9. Now, use Cube and Nightingale to make Herald of the Arc Light. This will trigger Cube, adding Telekinetic Charging Cell.
  10. Use Herald and Cross-Sheep to make Reprodocus (be sure that it's pointing to Stein).
  11. Change Stein to a Psychic-type, equip Charging Cell, and proceed to summon all of your remaining fusion monsters (you do not need to summon Dragoon to assemble lethal, as long as you remembered to use Nightingale's effect earlier. If you forgot, you must summon Dragoon to burn for lethal).
  12. Each Blaze Fenix, the Burning Bombardment Bird would burn for 1800 if you didn't summon Dragoon, and 2100 if you did. Windwitch - Crystal Bell can target Nightingale to deal 4000 damage, hence enough for an FTK.
If the FTK fails, make Dragoon through Predaplant Verte Anaconda. If you're going second, you've got Accesscode Talker. And to see the combo in action, check out this link: https://youtu.be/ViOdtRxz0Fc

I've decided that I'm going to update my decklists! Each one will go from 50 cards to 45 for some more consistency.  Shaddolls! The deck that seems to keep coming back into the meta scene! This Fusion-based deck is a fan-favorite for its' amazing strength! Personally, I just LOVE the designs of each and every card in this archetype AND the lore behind them!     Deck strategy coming soon!

Ah yes, Rokkets. The gun dragons (Dra-gun, if you will). These guys are pretty relevant to the meta game, and are surprisingly easy to pick up! Basically, your normal strategy is going to involve targeting your Rokket monsters with various Link monster effects (namely Striker Dragon, Booster Dragon, and the family of Borrels), activate the Rokket monster's effect, then at the end of the turn, special summon a different Rokket from the deck! These guys' biggest strengths include their ability to swarm the field and their quick effects, allowing various forms of destruction and removal (My personal favorite being Shelrokket Dragon). Another strength being their swole Link-4 Borrel dads and their crazy Topologic uncles. Want mass removal? Topologics. Want interruptions and the best way to trigger a Rokket? Borrels. Now for the interesting part. Namely, how their greatest strength is their greatest weakness: Graveyard effects. These guys can get really hurt if your opponent activates Called by the Grave or Silent Graveyard, so plan accordingly. Borreload Savage Dragon can ease that problem, so plan ahead with this sweet deck. Remember to have fun!

deck_excerpt: It's a nice deck to use, very fast, and very effective go 2nd.
deck_description: The main strategy on this deck is link summoning Double Dragon Lords to search for Lu Feng, which is the Master of the deck, as it can be easily summoned and pop some cards of the field. Also you can use DDL  and the Spells to search for Zhang Yuan or Zhang De if you have Ancient Warriors on the fiel. Guan Yun combined with Liu Xuang is a good start to fill your field with at least 3 monster with 3000+. Remember to put the Ancient Warriors S/T always, you need them to trigger some effects. Tri-Brigade are here to help on putting more cards on hand, especially if you didn't get the better hand. Also, Omen can swipe for 3000 which is always good.  I'm still figuring out how to draw and search for more cards. The biggest problem of Ancient Warrior is you can get your hands tied very often, so run 2 Reload and 2 Avarice, which proved to be very useful on my tests, however idk if they are the best strategy to keep my hand full or search for something when a strategy go wrong.  Ghost Ogre and Gnomaterial (not sure if i'll keep this one) are good, as you need to stop your opponent to summon powerful monsters because of Lu Feng negative effect. Tenki is very helpful if you need to search not only Ancients, but Tri-Brigade too, not so sure about Tensu.  I'm still thinking about the Extra, besides Blosson, Omen and DDL, the others were not very useful. The Side Deck is also a work in progress.

deck_excerpt: Use the swarming mechanics in this deck to quickly overwhelm your opponents and you might have a victory in your grasp!
deck_description: As one might know, this deck has one of the most popular cards in all of duel monsters: Blue-Eyes White Dragon.     "Blue-Eyes" Decks aim for a field control strategy, usually by destroying opponent monsters. They can Synchro Summon monsters such as Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon to lock down the opponent's field or help Summon stronger monsters and set up a Fusion Summon for a finishing move. "The White Stone of Legend" needs another effect to discard it and be able to use its Graveyard effect. Whereas both the Monster cards "Master" and "Sage with Eyes of Blue" have effects to Special Summon any "Blue-Eyes" Monster from the Main Deck by either "Shuffles itself from the Graveyard to the Main Deck" ('Spinning to Deck' for short) or Discards itself.  "Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon" can also can Tribute itself to Special Summon any LIGHT Dragon-type Synchro monster from your extra deck. "Blue-Eyes Twin Burst Dragon" is a Fusion Monster that does not need a "Polymerization"-like card to be Fusion Summoned. It cannot be destroyed by battle, can attack monsters twice during the Battle Phase and banishes any monster that it failed to destroy by battle."Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon" is a Ritual Monster that cannot be targeted or destroyed by card effects and can wipe out your opponent in a single display of doubled-piercing chaotic white lightning.

This deck is surprisingly good and has a lot of solid and consistent combos going for it: The ideal and most consistent combo you can do with this deck is:

Beautunaful Princess/Buzzsaw Shark + Generation Force/Xyz Remora = Utopic Future Dragon + Toadally Awesome (+ Bahamut Shark)/Abyss Dweller + 1 more Level 4 on the field + C101 next turn, if you happen to have a 2nd level 4 on the field you can complete the combo by XYZ summoning either the Bahamut Shark or Abyss Dweller, which ever you didn't summon:

  1. Summon Buzzsaw Shark
  2. Activate Buzzsaw, summon any Level 4 from deck
  3. XYZ into Bahamut Shark
  4. Activate Bahamut Shark, Summon Rebarian Shark
  5. Summon Full Armor Black Ray Lancer on top of Rebarian Shark
  6. Activate XYZ Remora, detach the two materials left
  7. Activate XYZ Remora's summoning effect, + Rebarian Shark's effect to put Rank-Up-Magic: The Seventh One on the top of the deck
  8. Special Summon the Level 4s in the grave
  9. Use Black Ray Lancer + Bahamut Shark to go into F0: Utopic Future then summon Utopic Future Dragon on top of that
  10. Go into Abyss Dweller or another Bahamut Shark (or both if you have another level 4 like XYZ Slidolphin or Silent Angler for example on the field or in your hand)
  11. If you went into Bahamut Shark again, activate it's effect to summon Toadally Awesome
As long as you have at least Buzzsaw Shark you can guarantee yourself a Utopic Future Dragon with a C101 next turn, the side deck includes the typical going 2nd cards as well as other extra deck monsters, Dragite can be brought out with White Stingray being summoned from the grave, which can be done pretty easily with Coral Anemone or White Mirror. Valiant Shark Lancer can be brought out with XYZ Revive Splash (which is most likely going to happen) or Lantern and Buzzsaw Shark. Megaclops is a very good card if you're going 2nd, as you can use it to bring back dead XYZ Monsters and give it materials, like Bahamut Shark. If you have any advice or other combos, let me know in the comments.

deck_excerpt: An Evigishki Gustkraken Hand Loop deck utilizing Crystron Halqifibrax combos.
deck_description:
Heya, it's been a while since I've posted a decklist, but I've been cooking up this Gishki Hand Loop deck for a hot minute and I think I've finally nailed it. As you would expect, this heavily abuses Crystron Halqifibrax + Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon combos and can pretty reliably rip 3-5 cards out of the opponent's hand, even with negates at play. I think this deck is at least a rogue-tier strategy. The main thing that makes this deck tick is Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince, as it sends Atlantean Dragoons for cost and thus isn't the type of thing someone wants to hand trap. You can get so much mileage off of that thing, it's insane. If you bring it out with Deep Sea Diva or One for One you're getting a full combo almost every time. Your general opening will be Diva -> Neptabyss, then climbing into Halq (bringing out Deskbot 001) and Auroradon, then using 001 + the tokens to bring out a Herald of the Arc Light. You can then destroy the remaining 2 tokens for Coltwing to bring out 2 more and revive 001, use that for a second Herald, then use both Heralds to go into Dugares. Detaching 2 Heralds and getting the draws with Dugares is a very big plus and you can often get significant mileage from it. You can alternatively run something like Nyarla or Daigusto Emeral with this, but I've found Dugares to be the most consistently good one. Unlike quite a few Gishki builds I've seen, I think Deskbot 003 is detrimental to the deck. It's incredibly easy to hand trap and doesn't synergize with the deck's goals outside of going into Halq combos. It's a good engine card at a glance but it requires the opponent to just let you proc it and we all know that's not going to happen, and that can be the end of the turn right there. By cutting it out you're increasing the consistency by dedicating your normal summon to Diva or Neptabyss, both of which you're near-guaranteed to see thanks to all the search/draw options (Dragoons + Minstrel, Deep Sea Dria, One for One, Dugares draws, Talents draws). I also like not having to use two 001s, which the 003 combo really likes, which decreases consistency further...it's just a mess. If you want to run it though, cut out the Talents and Upstart and you can see what I mean in practice. Anyway, onto the card reviews themselves. Monsters (24):
  • 1x Lapis Dragon
    • Great card to search off Dragoons to use as a combo piece. I like to do this with Minstrel + Dragoons since it's often a free Halq combo, but you can do it off the Neptabyss route if you really want to. If you get it in your opening hand it kinda sucks though.
  • 3x Atlantean Dragoons
    • Broken. If you drop this with Neptabyss or Minstrel you're able to get virtually anything you want in the deck: Gishki Shadow/Vision for a ritual search, Minstrel, Diva, all of these are ways to get balls-deep into that hand loop. You're free to run 2 if you're afraid of bricking, but you're often selling yourself short and losing out on a few routes.
  • 1x Mecha Phantom Beast Coltwing
    • Summon it with Auroradon to go + one million, you get the idea. The destruction effect is nice if you're going second too, I guess, but you're playing it for the opening combo. It's a really fun card!
  • 3x Gishki Shadow
    • This is your Aquamirror searcher, and sometimes a way to guarantee the final hand rip if you're short of cards. Also, this can trigger Deep Sea Aria after use, which is super helpful. If you're in a really tight spot for whatever reason, you can also use it as a Dugares material. Don't actually do that, though.
  • 3x Deep Sea Minstrel
    • I was running this at 1 until I started field testing this deck and man oh man is this card stupid. It's a perfect way to trigger the Dragoons in your hand while collecting data and helping secure your hand loop for the turn. It's just flat out insane and not maxing out will really hurt you in the long run. She also triggers Deep Sea Aria after use which is nice. I never find myself using her second effect though, it just kinda sucks?
  • 3x Gishki Vision
    • Gishki Shadow but it can be summoned with Deep Sea Diva for a Herald summon. Nifty little tech if you get Neptabyss out without her help.
  • 3x Deep Sea Diva
    • Using this to get out Neptabyss is your full Halqifibrax combo, and as such, you should never run less than 3. The heart and soul of this deck's combo starting antics.
    • Here is a good one card + junk opening from Diva you can use to start your combo routes;
      • NS Diva -> SS Neptabyss -> Neptabyss eff, pitch Dragoons -> Add Dragoons, GY Dragoons eff, search Deep Sea Minstrel -> Use Deep Sea Minstrel's effect to pitch Dragoons and rip out a card, proc Dragoons to search Gishki Vision -> Link Neptabyss and Diva for Halq -> SS Deskbot 001 -> Climb into Auroradon, summon 3 tokens, trigger 001 in GY -> Synchro 001 + token for Herald -> Auroradon 2nd eff, destroy 2 tokens, summon Coltwing -> Coltwing eff, summon 2 tokens, trigger GY 001 -> Synchro 001 + token for Herald -> Xyz both Heralds for Dugares -> Dugares 1st eff, draw 2 discard 1, detach both Heralds, discard junk -> trigger both Heralds, search Gustkraken + Aquamirror -> pitch Vision from earlier for another Gustkraken -> Summon your first.
      • From here, continue your plays utilizing your Dugares draws and other parts of your starting hand.
      • You have the option of stopping at Halq to go into Desert Locusts on the opponent's turn if you have enough to go into a 4-card hand loop. This can be further extended into going into Baroness de Fleur, Borreload Savage Dragon, or PSY-Framelord Omega depending on the materials you have on your board. Absolutely experiment with this, it's a very good route. The first sign you should try this route is if you have a One for One in hand since Neptabyss is largely what enables the route.
  • 3x Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince
    • Ballbustingly good card, pitching Atlantean Dragoons for cost to trigger its effect while searching you another. This is a one-card way to trigger Minstrel while activating the Dragoons you searched, which leads to a +1 in card advantage overall. This doesn't interrupt your combo plays at all and you should never skip out on it.  If you don't have Diva, normal summon this and you won't be too impeded.
  • 1x Deskbot 001
    • For Halq and nothing else. Pray you don't draw it.
  • 3x Evigishki Gustkraken
    • Literally a safer Topologic Gumblar Dragon.
Spells (16):
  • 1x One for One
    • Summons Neptabyss from the deck for what's basically free, giving you a possible route of fetching Deep Sea Diva w/Aria to go into more lengthy combos. You can also summon Deskbot 001 if you're on shrooms or something I guess.
    • Including Beautunaful Princess + Gishki Abyss can make this a free search but it kinda sucks honestly, I wouldn't go for it these days but the option is there.
  • 3x Three Tactical Talents
    • Great contingency plan against hand traps since they're absolutely going to negate your stuff. This'll normally be Diva. Collect your Draw 2 if you want to continue popping off, but the hand rip is also an acceptable option if you think the negate is going to stop the full combo. Look at what backup combo pieces you have before making the decision.
  • 1x Extra-Foolish Burial
    • I'd run more but drawing 2+ of these fucking sucks, man. This is a hand loop deck so you really want to max out on the non-HOPT cards unless they're absolutely necessary, which this isn't. Anyway, pitch Herald and call it a day.
    • If you're going to run 3, cut Photomirror and Upstart Goblin.
  • 1x Upstart Goblin
    •  39 Card Deck, yup.
  • 3x Deep Sea Aria
    • Effortless to proc since you're burying those Gishki Shadows and Visions like your life depends on it. You can also banish one of the Dragoons. This searches you more Gishki Shadows and Visions to continue the hand loop, which is insanely useful.
  • 3x Preparation of Rites
    • With this, you can make an excuse to cut a Vision, since this'll be grabbing you Gustkraken while getting an Aquamirror back. This is basically Pot of Greed and it's not even OPT for some reason. God, why is that a thing?
  • 1x Gishki Photomirror
    • There'll be times where you're a material short when trying to release the Kraken, which this remedies. Plus, if you have a Preparation of Rites in hand after using this, that becomes a "one-card" Gustkraken without having to tribute the one you previously summoned. Thus, that gives you a Rank 6. I don't see many people running this, so maybe I'm using this for the wrong reasons. Very cuttable, I just like the flexibility.
  • 3x Gishki Aquamirror
    • The main spell you're using to loop Gustkraken, don't think I need to explain that.
Extra (15):
  • 1x Baroness de Fleur (or Geomathmech Final Sigma)
    • You can bring this out with Diva + 2 L4s, Desert Locusts + 1 L4 or something, which is a free negate on the board for your torn-up opponent to get through. This often secures the win unless they got something real special. If using Geomathmech you can get that more easily with Desert Locusts + Gustkraken.
  • 1x Borreload Savage Dragon
    • Good card to use after a Halq combo; again, this normally secures a win because of the negate.
  • 1x PSY-Framelord Omega
    • Another way to secure a hand loop at the end of a turn, can be summoned with Desert Locusts + an L2 as well, which few decks can pull off. If you're not able to hand loop for more than 3, try going for a Locusts + L2 play with this!
  • 3x Herald of the Arc Light
    • Your searchers and a funny negate + pseudo-vanitys if you can keep one on deck. Never run less than 3.
  • 1x Constellar Ptolemy M7
    • Straight from the 2013 build baby, this card still has it. Use this to get your Shadow back from the grave after proccing Aquamirror to continue the Gustkraken loop.
  • 1x Virtual World Phoenix - Fanfan
    • You can also run Photon Strike Bounzer, but this deck is very weak going second and this has helped a lot in that regard. Detaches two Gustkrakens to banish a card from their hand and GY, which you can use to proc an otherwise dead Aquamirror too. Generally a really nice card.
  • 1x Number 60: Dugares the Timeless
    • You're generally only using Dugares for his draw effect, but the SS from GY can be handy if you're willing to forsake a follow-up. Anyway, the draw effect is largely what keeps him here, so if you want to use Dweller or Nyarla then by all means do so. Nyarla is particularly nice alongside the Heralds since you're possibly getting 3 searches off it.
  • 1x Accesscode Talker
    • Bonk.
  • 1x Knightmare Unicorn
    • Use this when going second to make life easier, and then climb into Accesscode Talker to swing for game. No other reason for using it, but it's a very good reason regardless!
  • 1x Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon
    • Bonk but for going first.
  • 2x Crystron Halqifibrax
    • Running 2 to give this deck a better follow-up post-hand loop, but you can drop the second if you have any better ideas. This card should be banned sometimes though ahahaha

deck_description: Hand/Deck Tampering

This Deck focuses on summoning high level Insect monsters, including the infamous Perfectly Ultimate Great Moth. I put several Insect cards with special summon and search effects to easily summon the deck's ace monster,  Metamorphosed Insect Queen. I have three main strategies for this deck:
  1. Parasite Infection: Equip opponent's monsters with Parasite Paranoid, then activates Cocoon of Ultra Evolution to summon Perfectly Moth or Insect Queen. You can use it to get rid of strong monsters, even though it didn't work against Untargetable monsters.
  2. Switcheroo: Use Creature Swap to steal a opponent's monster, giving them a Worm Bait/Insect Queen token. It's more efficient than the Parasite Infection strategy, i recommend use it to do a Beatdown or get a strong monster to your side.
  3.  Gozen Match: Many decks/archtypes have different attributes, so this can be a pain. This is a stall strategy, use this to hold the opponent's back while getting the right cards to do some of the other 2 combos.  Remember  the Deck is composed of Earth monsters, so think twice before use it.
Gokipon can search for Parasite Paranoid, while Howling Insect can summon Gokipole from the Deck, allowing you to use the Gokipole + Gokibore combo effect, and considering the Gokipole effect didn't target, you can get rid of stronger opponent's monster in a more efficient way. Use Pinch Hopper to summon Insect Queen from your hand (if you have it) destroying him or used it for a Link Summon, for example. Cocoon of Ultra Evolution it's the most important card of this deck, and if you didn't draw it on the first turn, you'll need to hold the game a bit until you draw Cocoon. Your biggest problem will be the opponent's set cards. Feel free to add any other card to this decklist to supply this failure. I plan to update this on the future, but for now, is this.
I'm a crazy person, but this is yet the most constitent, versatile and recoverable deck i've had. Dead hand at 1/25 also.

Considering all the Change cards are Quick-Spells, you can use them into the Battle Phase to OTK, depending of which cards you have.

Episode 0.5 Deck
This deck is a budget hero variant

Here’s the build I’m planning on using for the 2021 format when lightning overdrive comes out with exlord and rekindled rebirth. And yes, surprise, I’m doing laval.

So here’s the list, the deck is a little pricy but it won’t murder you.

2 laval burner

Laval burner can special summon itself from your hand if you have 3 or more laval monsters with different names in your graveyard. It’s a level 5 monster with 1000 defense sadly, because most of the deck likes 200 defense but burner still gets 2 slots in my build for being a free body and is probably the only level 5 or higher laval worth playing in the game at the moment.

3 neo-flamvell lady

Neo-flamvell lady is one of the best cards to run in a laval deck like this one. It gives you a way to stop eldlich and other similar decks with a quick effect, and as an added bonus mills monsters directly from your deck to fill your graveyard with laval monsters! I gave it 3 slots purely for how well it works with laval in general.

3 laval blaster

Laval blaster can dump up to 5 cards off the top of your deck to the grave upon its normal summon provided you already have a laval in your graveyard. This is easily a common situation and laval archer can help you out with summoning it. Though it has 800 defense I still played it at three because of the sheer number of cards it can mill.

3 laval archer

Laval archer is super good. It can self revive for releveling, it provides another normal summon if you use it for a laval monster, and it has out magic 200 defense stat! I honestly love this card in general and I find it to be one of the best tools laval has at the moment, I gave it 3 spots for how helpful it is.

1 laval lakeside lady

This card can destroy a set card but it’s main flaw is that it also ends up clearing your graveyard. You can mill this monster often enough that I only feel to play 1.

3 ash blossom and joyous spring

Ash blossom and joyous spring is one of the best handtraps in the format and not only that but it’s a fire monster! I gave it three slots because if ash is in your deck, it going at 3.

3 laval coatl

Laval coatl is similar to laval burner but it’s a level 2 tuner. Just for being a tuner that can summon itself it got 3 slots

1 laval forest sprite

Laval forest sprite can make your laval gain huge amounts of stats but it really is only being played for being a level 2 200 defense fire tuner.

3 laval volcano handmaiden

Laval handmaiden is an inanely useful card who mills 3 laval monsters! It also has 200 defense so you can mass spawn it with rekindling

3 de-synchro

De-synchro is a spell that takes apart a synchro monster, you can use it to take apart salamander and make dawn dragster or even repeat synchro monster effects.

3 molten construction field

This is an absolute 3 of in laval decks! It can fill out 5 laval monsters combined with handmaiden

1 rekindled rebirth

Grave tunes 200 defense fire monsters but it is a little bricky over one, it’s a nice tool to have regardless though.

3 rekindling

Oh my god, this is toadally staying at 3 in this build, it summons a lot and is a great card in general.

3 searing fire wall

Summons as many tokens as you like. It’s a great tool in this deck.

2 flamvell counter

This can banish a 200 defense fire in your graveyard to stop a spell/trap, I play it because of the sheer amount of 200 defense fires I can mill.

3 infinite impenitence

Free negate

I think the extra deck is mostly self explanatory except for my choice of “Laval Dragon” not “Laval Dragun” whose completely explanatory but dragOn. So why? Simply put its effect is actually super good. It can shuffle 2 laval monsters from your graveyard into your deck to return a card from the field to the hand, but it’s not a hard once per turn which means as long as you have the laval monsters in your graveyard to work with you can keep on doing it, and you mill a ton of laval monsters really quickly with this deck.

None of the combos are exactly linear but you have multiple ways start things and alongside the drawpower this deck provides I’ll admit that in the right hands I feel laval can be a pretty good deck.

Things to consider when piloting this deck:

1: always pick a target if any before summoning neo-flamvell lady and only use her if your opponent has a graveyard, sure she’s a quick effect and everything but you don’t have much protection for her.

2: when using molten construction field try milling handmaiden, handmaiden cane mill two mor handmaidens and then pitch another laval of your choice.

3: if you’re confident about being able to do it and still summon other synchros then summon T.G. hyper librarian when possible.

I didn’t pick out a side deck yet because I don’t know what will happen in the future but if you have any ideas for a side deck then feel free to tell me!

deck_excerpt: Another fun to play mill deck that utilises Zombie World and a Zoodiac XYZ chain to mill upto 36+ cards in 1 turn :)
deck_description: Okayy I'll try keep this one shorter than my last deck.. and yes I'm using Comic Sans again :) SO this deck is a whole bunch of fun, I must admit the idea of using Zoodiacs was not mine, although I cannot remember who I stole it from.. XD Anyway,, the goal of this deck is simply to simply mill your opponent's whole deck. You probably won't be able to deplete their life points, so this is really the only win condition Main Strategy: -Getting 3 bone towers is relatively easy, just special summon one and then use your Inferno Reckless Summon to pull out all 3. Sometimes you won't be able to summon all 3, or you may not need all 3, however the more you have, the more cards you can mill. -Next up, you need a Chakanine. It requires 2 level 4 monsters, which is easy to achieve with the Uni Zombie card. (Don't be afraid to use a tower as material if needed. You can mill 12 cards per tower with this chain, so do the math and find out how many you need to win.) -Finally we have Zombie World. Now, ZW can sometimes be a pain to get out, however cards such as Necroworld Banshee and Terraforming should make it easier if you don't draw it :). Zombie World is arguably the most important card in this combo, without it, the Zoodiacs won't count as zombie types, and therefore will not trigger bone tower. Protect it as well as you can. After you pull off this and mill 12-36 cards of your opponent's deck, simply use your leftover Zoodiac and a tower to summon Vampire Sucker to mill another 4, and use Sucker's effect for yet another 4 cards, bringing the total number of cards milled to 44 (with 3 towers) Side Strategy: - If for some reason your Zoodiacs get stopped, there are other cards that could help mill a few more cards and earn that sweet victory :) - You can suicide your pyramid turtles (with bone tower on the field) in order to special another turtle from the deck, rinse and repeat 3 times to mill 6-18 cards. If done strategically, you can use the last turtle to pull out a Solitaire, who then sacrifices itself and specials yet another zombie. Use this to summon Uni Zombie, and hey presto, you have a gateway to another zombie, just use uni to grave a Mezuki, and then use Mezuki's effect. All in all, this seems pretty good, there are many ways to special summon zombie monsters, but unfortunately I cannot go over them all :P A few things to note before I go: - PSY-Framelord Omega, Burial from a Different Dimension, and Leviair the Sea Dragon's effect allows you to recycle Mezuki over and over, use it wisely :) - There is a smaller Utopia XYZ chain in the extra deck for incase the Zoodiacs fail. It is not as big but works well in a pinch. - A Mechquipped Angineer summoned in attack position can protect you for 2 turns if you need to stall. - Minerva the Exalted Lightsworn is able to mill 3 cards from your own deck. This can be favourable in some cases, but be wary that spells and traps are at risk too. - If your oponent has a 40+ card deck, choose to go second. Let your opponent play their turn, shorten their deck and make your job a little easier. If they have a 40 card deck then it doesn't matter so much since they'll only have 35 cards left for you to mill, perfect for an OTK with the right hand   And yeah, that's about it :) If I come across any issues or updates to the deck I'll be sure to edit this post or even create a new one :P Again, feel free to message my discord (Katsuki#8104) with any questions or suggestions, or just comment on the post (I check in on this site every few days, so Discord would be much faster if that's what you're after) Goodbye and thanks for reading :)

deck_excerpt: This deck is really strong with a lock strategy
deck_description:
Hi everyone, my name is Jakzyte and i'm a budget player. I will quickly define what is being a budget player for me and then talk about the deck strategy and the choices i made.   Budget : Is constructing a strategy to be as efficient possible with the least amount of money. I wouldn't for example pay 20 bucks for a card and the total price range of the deck should be around 100 €, but of course this can vary depending if I really like the archetype or not. The point is also to buy cards that could be used in other strategies to save a little bit of money in the yu gi oh journey. So here i'm presenting a the Tri-Brigrade strategy, which has become one of my favourite archetypes. If everything works out fine i will be posting 3 vesions of Tri-Brigade :
  1. Classic lyrlusc control version
  2. Trap Zoo more popular in the OCG
  3. Harpie Tri-brigade which is actually insane
  I play psy-framed gamma as Handtrap just because it's so good AND it is basically an copy of called by the grave, it facilitate your plays. D.D Crow could be switched out depending on the need I just like it because it's a winged beast that could either searched or could be discarded. Then everything is normal ratio wise until you see that i play 6 traps. The 3 Tri-Brigade Revolte let's you have a free 3000 body who banishes somehting on the turn of your ennemy. It is not mandatory since it conflicts with the Barrier Statue lock, but i haven't had any issues with that throught the playtesting yet. The most important trap is Harpie's Feather Storm. This card is broken... and i'm really affraid to show it because this card alone let's you win games. It synergises very well with lyrlusc since they are wind winged beast monsters. You can set this card at the beginning of your plays to ensure you to go into your full combo since it shuts down handtraps. Or you could simply add an omni monster negate for the turn to your lock.
